246. Perque to be pronomeed pere (cf. uee for neque, ae i.e. ‘ate’ for atque3 see Introd. ii. ξ 14). Hostica has here the sense of ‘hostile,' but in Mil. 450 that of ‘strange’z hosticum hoe mihi domicilium θείς Atheuis domus est. The form was old-fashioned in the Augustan Age, as we see from Porphyrio's note on Horace C. 11. 1. 1 : adtende autem uon ‘civile' sed ‘civicum' dixisse antiqua fiyura. Illi enim ‘civica' et ‘hostiea,' deiude ‘civilia' et ‘hostilia' dicebaut. The first syllable of the word is not to be scanned short in this line. The fourth foot is a dactyl (-muue quod), as in v. 570 and elsewhere (see Introd. iii. ξ 17). Some editors transpose quod commuue to avoid the irregular division of the dactyl (Introd. iii. ξ 16).

247. Honore honestes, a jingling phrase that occurs again in V. 356. (See note on v, 107 moratus moribus).

248. Qui fueris. Before consonants qui, not quis, is nel-mally used in indireet questions in Plautus and Terence, eg. M il. 261 qui fuerit eouseruos (AF), Pseud. 263 seio qui fuit (ΑΡ).
